note: A certification of the gift by the United States Minister in Tehran laid in.

msContents.summary: Small, neatly written, gilded copy with embroidered cover and carrying case.

name.#text: Free Library of Philadelphia. Rare Book Department. John Frederick Lewis Collection of Oriental Manuscripts

persName.#text: Sālār al-Dawlah, Abū al-Fatḥ Mīrzā, 1880 or 1881-1959

msItem.title: Letter of presentation from U.S. Minister in Tehran

supportDesc.extent: 134 leaves : 107 x 65 (80 x 40) mm bound to 110 x 65 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation added in pencil, upper left recto; catchwords every verso, lower left.

layoutDesc.layout: Chiefly 14 long lines, sometimes half the page in diagonal or perpendicular and half the page straight across; border-ruled.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻliq shikastah in black ink; pointed.

decoNote: Illuminated headpiece in gold, red, blue, green on first opening (f. 1v). The entire text written on cloudbands; textblock double border-ruled in gold; page-opening ruled in black; rubrications in red.

binding.p: Embroidered covers of alternating stripes of dark and light with floral motifs over card with green leather edges and spine; gold stamped frame; green leather pastedowns. Matching green leather carrying box with red textile interior. Case is stamped "Gulistan Persian MS."

origin.p: The item is undated, but likely produced in the 18th century.

provenance: Gift of Anne Baker Lewis in 1933.
Gift of Abū al-Fatḥ Mīrzā, Sālār al-Dawlah, third son of Muẓaffar al-Dīn Shāh to Oliver Henry Perkins, April 11, 1901 (inscription last flyleaf recto and notes laid in).
Formerly owned by Oliver Henry Perkins (bookplate inside front cover).
Sold in Perkins' sale at Anderson Galleries on March 23 and 24, 1926 (catalog entry laid in).
Formerly owned by John Frederick Lewis.

term: Illumination of books and manuscripts, Iranian--Specimens
